WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.027 --> 00:00:03.110
MIMI KRAVETZ: Hi everyone.

00:00:03.110 --> 00:00:04.880
Welcome to the Talks
at Google event

00:00:04.880 --> 00:00:07.490
on "Supersurvivors:
The Surprising Link

00:00:07.490 --> 00:00:10.802
Between Suffering and Success."

00:00:10.802 --> 00:00:13.980
In a moment, I'll introduce
you to the authors, Lee Daniel

00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:17.120
Kravetz and David B.
Feldman, but first I

00:00:17.120 --> 00:00:18.940
wanted to steal the
floor because I'm not

00:00:18.940 --> 00:00:21.360
only the Googler who's
organizing this event,

00:00:21.360 --> 00:00:24.760
but I'm also Lee's wife, and
I've been part of this book

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:26.310
since the very beginning.

00:00:26.310 --> 00:00:30.530
So five years ago, Lee
and I went for a walk,

00:00:30.530 --> 00:00:34.080
and he had just
survived his own trauma,

00:00:34.080 --> 00:00:36.060
and we were talking
about how he really

00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:38.120
wanted to do something
meaningful in the world

00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:40.460
coming out of that.

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:43.820
And we were also talking about
how every time he told people

00:00:43.820 --> 00:00:47.730
about his experience, we heard
the most incredible stories

00:00:47.730 --> 00:00:48.670
back.

00:00:48.670 --> 00:00:52.170
And we wondered
what factors went

00:00:52.170 --> 00:00:53.980
into how somebody
experiences a trauma

00:00:53.980 --> 00:00:56.586
and how they come out of it.

00:00:56.586 --> 00:01:00.080
And that was really the germ of
an idea that led to this book.

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:05.129
And so, it's so awesome
to be here today

00:01:05.129 --> 00:01:08.350
introducing Lee and Dave to
talk about their published

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:12.200
book that's out
there in the world.

00:01:12.200 --> 00:01:14.010
Lee Daniel Kravetz
has a master's degree

00:01:14.010 --> 00:01:16.450
in Counseling Psychology
and is a graduate

00:01:16.450 --> 00:01:19.420
of the University of Missouri
School of Journalism.

00:01:19.420 --> 00:01:22.000
He's held positions at the
VA Palo Alto Health Care

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.330
System, the National Center
for PTSD, Stanford University

00:01:26.330 --> 00:01:30.467
Hospital, and now works at a
private practice in Palo Alto.

00:01:30.467 --> 00:01:32.050
He's written for
print and television,

00:01:32.050 --> 00:01:35.440
including the New York
Times, Psychology Today,

00:01:35.440 --> 00:01:39.600
Huffington Post, as well as
Frontline, NOVA, and Sesame

00:01:39.600 --> 00:01:43.430
Street, which our three-year-old
is thrilled about.

00:01:43.430 --> 00:01:45.950
He lives in the San
Francisco Bay Area with me

00:01:45.950 --> 00:01:47.470
and our two very cute kids.

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:52.080
David B. Feldman
is considered to be

00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:56.330
among the top experts on hope
in the field of psychology.

00:01:56.330 --> 00:01:59.420
He's an Associate Professor
of Counseling Psychology

00:01:59.420 --> 00:02:01.280
at Santa Clara University.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:04.670
He holds a PhD in Clinical
Psychology from the University

00:02:04.670 --> 00:02:07.910
of Kansas and completed
a postdoctoral fellowship

00:02:07.910 --> 00:02:10.830
in the VA Palo Alto
Health Care System ,

00:02:10.830 --> 00:02:13.920
a medical center associated
with Stanford University.

00:02:13.920 --> 00:02:16.380
Dr. Feldman is the author
of two previous books

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:19.340
and has written for Psychology
Today and the Huffington Post

00:02:19.340 --> 00:02:22.160
and published numerous
research articles.

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:23.920
He lives in the San
Francisco Bay Area

00:02:23.920 --> 00:02:25.738
with his partner
who's also here today.

00:02:25.738 --> 00:02:27.071
DAVID FELDMAN: And adorable cat.

00:02:29.804 --> 00:02:31.720
MIMI KRAVETZ: And they
will be in conversation

00:02:31.720 --> 00:02:34.770
with Dan Ariely.

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:37.530
Dan is the James B. Duke
Professor of Psychology

00:02:37.530 --> 00:02:40.460
and Behavioral Economics
at Duke University

00:02:40.460 --> 00:02:42.370
and is the author of
New York Times Best

00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:44.470
Sellers, "Predictably
Irrational,"

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:47.760
"The Upside of Rationality,"
and "The Honest Truth About

00:02:47.760 --> 00:02:49.270
Dishonesty."

00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:52.320
And Dan also works with
us here at Google now.

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:56.060
In the SP&amp;E team in
the Irrational Labs.

00:02:56.060 --> 00:02:59.180
It's a great honor to introduce
all three of these gentlemen

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:00.904
and I'll turn it over to them.

00:03:00.904 --> 00:03:07.259
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:07.259 --> 00:03:08.300
DAVID FELDMAN: Thank you.

00:03:08.300 --> 00:03:09.424
Can you hear me OK?

00:03:09.424 --> 00:03:11.590
Is this OK or do I need to
speak more into the mike?

00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:14.100
I've got my little lapel thing.

00:03:14.100 --> 00:03:16.070
I think what we'll
do is I'll talk

00:03:16.070 --> 00:03:18.880
for a few minutes about the
journey that led us to write

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:21.890
this book and a little bit
about our process writing it.

00:03:21.890 --> 00:03:23.309
Lee will talk a little bit.

00:03:23.309 --> 00:03:25.100
We'll read from the
book for a few minutes,

00:03:25.100 --> 00:03:28.280
and then we will take our
positions here on these chairs

00:03:28.280 --> 00:03:31.140
and have a little conversation.

00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:34.720
And Dan is prepared to
ask us some questions.

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:38.000
So first of all, it's great
to see so many people here.

00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:40.580
I'm told the people tend to
come two or three minutes late

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:44.810
to these events, and people
were here early, which is great.

00:03:44.810 --> 00:03:48.150
Sorry we were a little
late getting started.

00:03:48.150 --> 00:03:52.340
I didn't know it, walking into
my Foundations of Personality

00:03:52.340 --> 00:03:56.110
and Psychotherapy class
in the Fall of 2010.

00:03:56.110 --> 00:03:59.690
But I was about to embark on a
fun and meaningful and exciting

00:03:59.690 --> 00:04:04.870
journey that would bring me and
Lee up until this very point.

00:04:04.870 --> 00:04:06.385
As Mimi told you
a second ago, I'm

00:04:06.385 --> 00:04:08.070
a Professor at Santa
Clara University,

00:04:08.070 --> 00:04:10.240
just down the street from here.

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:13.866
And I teach one of the most
boring classes on earth,

00:04:13.866 --> 00:04:15.740
Foundations of Personality
and Psychotherapy.

00:04:15.740 --> 00:04:18.550
This is the class that I think
a lot of students dread taking

00:04:18.550 --> 00:04:20.380
because we go through theory.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:22.040
It's just a theory
course, and they

00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:24.130
have to take tests
and write papers.

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:26.170
And these people want
to be counselors.

00:04:26.170 --> 00:04:27.440
So that's not their thing.

00:04:27.440 --> 00:04:30.180
So we talk about Freud, and we
talk about cognitive theory,

00:04:30.180 --> 00:04:33.550
and we talk about humanistic
and person-centered approaches

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:35.350
to how the mind works.

00:04:35.350 --> 00:04:38.380
And I try to keep it a little
lively and a little interesting

00:04:38.380 --> 00:04:41.090
so less people will fall asleep.

00:04:41.090 --> 00:04:43.230
I didn't know it
walking in that day,

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:47.060
but it would be one of the most
meaningful groups of students

00:04:47.060 --> 00:04:48.999
that I would ever teach.

00:04:48.999 --> 00:04:50.540
It was a fantastic
group of students.

00:04:50.540 --> 00:04:52.690
I can see the classroom now.

00:04:52.690 --> 00:04:56.300
And seated in the middle,
in the very middle--

00:04:56.300 --> 00:04:58.850
it was a stepped classroom,
and on the second step,

00:04:58.850 --> 00:05:02.297
in the very center-- was
a guy named Lee Kravetz.

00:05:02.297 --> 00:05:03.880
And I didn't know
his name at the time

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:07.430
because I'm the jerk who doesn't
learn students names very

00:05:07.430 --> 00:05:08.990
easily.

00:05:08.990 --> 00:05:10.610
I still don't.

00:05:10.610 --> 00:05:11.940
What is your name?

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:15.630
But I would learn it about
three or four weeks later,

00:05:15.630 --> 00:05:18.680
when I would give a
lecture on Existentialism.

00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:21.180
So for those of you who aren't
familiar with Existentialism,

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:25.110
it is a psychological
perspective, these days,

00:05:25.110 --> 00:05:28.030
imported from German philosophy.

00:05:28.030 --> 00:05:30.060
People like Nietzsche.

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:32.260
And it has a lot of
German words in it

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:33.720
that bore the heck
out of people.

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:38.080
So I try to keep students awake
by asking them pesky questions,

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:40.667
and asking them to
do pesky things that

00:05:40.667 --> 00:05:42.000
are designed to make them think.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:43.670
For instance I ask
them to calculate

00:05:43.670 --> 00:05:46.640
how many years they
have left to live.

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:48.410
And then I ask
them how much time

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:51.247
they've wasted up
until this point.

00:05:51.247 --> 00:05:53.580
And generally I get-- sort
of like you did right there--

00:05:53.580 --> 00:05:56.200
blank stares in
response to this.

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.070
Sometimes people come up and
say it was a meaningful question

00:05:59.070 --> 00:06:02.120
to ask, and it changed
the way that they thought.

00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:05.320
But what I noticed is that
Lee started to tear up.

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:09.110
And it's rare in a master's
class in Counseling Psychology

00:06:09.110 --> 00:06:11.840
that someone starts crying
in the middle of a lecture.

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:14.254
Perhaps it was
because it was boring.

00:06:14.254 --> 00:06:18.990
I later found out though that
he came across that tear very

00:06:18.990 --> 00:06:20.680
honestly.

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:23.900
As Mimi mentioned, he had
suffered his own trauma.

00:06:23.900 --> 00:06:28.810
At the age of 29, Lee suffered
an ordeal with cancer, one

00:06:28.810 --> 00:06:31.610
that he would
eventually win, but that

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:34.020
made him question whether
he was going to die.

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:38.530
Something that somebody at the
age of 29 shouldn't have to do.

00:06:38.530 --> 00:06:41.770
And as a result, he
dramatically changed his life.

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:45.110
He went from someone who was
working in New York as a book

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:47.380
publicist-- very
convenient when you've just

00:06:47.380 --> 00:06:51.970
written a book-- to
moving out here, getting

00:06:51.970 --> 00:06:54.160
his graduate degree in
Counseling Psychology

00:06:54.160 --> 00:06:56.790
and eventually
becoming an author.

00:06:56.790 --> 00:06:58.710
Now this sounds a lot
like our definition

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:00.820
in the book of what
a supersurvivor is.

00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:06.060
Someone who encounters a trauma,
a tragedy, an illness, a loss,

00:07:06.060 --> 00:07:08.340
some major adversity
in their life, and then

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:11.370
not only bounces back
but bounces forward,

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:14.060
often revolutionizing
their life for the better,

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:17.650
and often touching the world
around them in positive ways.

00:07:17.650 --> 00:07:19.790
Now I had done,
for years, therapy

00:07:19.790 --> 00:07:22.310
with people who were
suffering from trauma

00:07:22.310 --> 00:07:26.670
and serious medical
illness, and my research

00:07:26.670 --> 00:07:29.840
has all concerned how people
not only bounce back but bounce

00:07:29.840 --> 00:07:32.290
forward in the wake of trauma.

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:37.110
And so this started a series
of conversations between us

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:41.890
that culminated in a summer
independent study project

00:07:41.890 --> 00:07:44.120
where we worked together,
and Lee ended up

00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:46.150
writing a stunning,
I think 20-page,

00:07:46.150 --> 00:07:49.810
paper on some of the factors
that help people to bounce back

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:51.090
from trauma.

00:07:51.090 --> 00:07:53.352
I think it's safe to say
that that 20-page paper,

00:07:53.352 --> 00:07:54.810
and that independent
study project,

00:07:54.810 --> 00:07:57.020
turned into one of the
most epic independent study

00:07:57.020 --> 00:08:00.770
projects of all time and
eventually this book.

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:04.300
At some point, we were seated
in Nervous Dog Coffee on Mission

00:08:04.300 --> 00:08:07.050
Street in San Francisco, and
we just looked at each other

00:08:07.050 --> 00:08:09.200
and said there's a book here.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:12.010
And the rest is not
exactly history,

00:08:12.010 --> 00:08:14.820
but I will let Lee
catch you up from there.

00:08:14.820 --> 00:08:16.879
LEE DANIEL KRAVETZ:
Sounds great.

00:08:16.879 --> 00:08:17.420
Thanks, Dave.

00:08:20.260 --> 00:08:22.130
As we've kind of
talked about, this

00:08:22.130 --> 00:08:25.600
is as much about
other people as it

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:27.510
is our own personal journeys.

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:30.330
And my experience-- I
was a cancer survivor,

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:34.226
and when I bounced back from
it I became intensely focused

00:08:34.226 --> 00:08:36.309
on the ways that other
people kind of bounce back.

00:08:36.309 --> 00:08:37.892
How in the world do
people bounce back

00:08:37.892 --> 00:08:40.780
not only after cancer but all
kinds of crazy experiences

00:08:40.780 --> 00:08:41.740
in their lives.

00:08:41.740 --> 00:08:45.070
Everything from natural
disasters to car accidents.

00:08:45.070 --> 00:08:47.170
The things we have no
control over to things we do

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:48.770
have control over.

00:08:48.770 --> 00:08:53.590
And then I met Dave, and Dave
is a Professor of Counseling

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:56.700
Psychology, but he's
also an expert in hope.

00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:59.730
And when I met Dave, I knew that
there was a partnership here.

00:08:59.730 --> 00:09:02.190
We had to start writing
and working together.

00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:05.330
His research has
been the foundation

00:09:05.330 --> 00:09:08.490
of a lot of the
studies that have

00:09:08.490 --> 00:09:11.690
worked toward a
positive psychology.

00:09:11.690 --> 00:09:14.470
The study of hope in general
is just fascinating stuff,

00:09:14.470 --> 00:09:14.979
trust me.

00:09:14.979 --> 00:09:16.520
I can't even go
there because I don't

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:17.490
know what I'm talking about.

00:09:17.490 --> 00:09:19.573
But Dave does, so you
should talk to him about it.

00:09:19.573 --> 00:09:23.580
But he said to us early on, he
said, yes there's a book here.

00:09:23.580 --> 00:09:25.060
We need to expand it.

00:09:25.060 --> 00:09:26.210
Beyond cancer.

00:09:26.210 --> 00:09:28.850
But also look at all the
different types of trauma

00:09:28.850 --> 00:09:30.600
that people experience.

00:09:30.600 --> 00:09:34.620
And we spent months and
months defining and redefining

00:09:34.620 --> 00:09:36.620
what a supersurvivor was.

00:09:36.620 --> 00:09:38.810
And this was all
based on the research.

00:09:38.810 --> 00:09:40.644
There's 20 years-- two
decades-- of research

00:09:40.644 --> 00:09:42.643
that talks about what
we're going to talk about,

00:09:42.643 --> 00:09:43.909
called post-traumatic growth.

00:09:43.909 --> 00:09:45.950
We've all heard of
post-traumatic stress disorder

00:09:45.950 --> 00:09:48.580
and the negative side of trauma,
but post-traumatic growth

00:09:48.580 --> 00:09:50.490
is a pretty
spectacular phenomenon,

00:09:50.490 --> 00:09:55.990
and it happens quite often,
much more than PTSD, in fact.

00:09:55.990 --> 00:09:58.540
And we dove into the
research, and the research

00:09:58.540 --> 00:09:59.520
was fascinating.

00:09:59.520 --> 00:10:03.760
We saw things that
were counter-intuitive

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:05.880
that we'll talk about
a little bit later.

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:07.830
Things that just really
sparked our interest

00:10:07.830 --> 00:10:10.600
about these clinicians, and
researchers, and writers.

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:16.690
And then we started matching
up case studies-- examples that

00:10:16.690 --> 00:10:18.260
mapped perfectly
onto the science.

00:10:18.260 --> 00:10:19.460
And that's when we
got to actually meet

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:20.251
our supersurvivors.

00:10:22.506 --> 00:10:23.880
We started with
one or two and it

00:10:23.880 --> 00:10:26.000
expanded to about 150 people.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:29.882
We pared it down
to 17 for the book,

00:10:29.882 --> 00:10:31.247
but these people were amazing.

00:10:31.247 --> 00:10:33.330
I mean, this was one of
the best parts of our job.

00:10:33.330 --> 00:10:34.746
We got to hang out
with people who

00:10:34.746 --> 00:10:37.380
had survived remarkable,
remarkable things,

00:10:37.380 --> 00:10:41.380
and then gone on to change their
lives dramatically as a result.

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.460
We met Asha Mevlana,
who we're going

00:10:43.460 --> 00:10:45.940
to read about in a few
minutes, who went from a cancer

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:48.840
survivor, like me, but did
something remarkable with it.

00:10:48.840 --> 00:10:51.730
We met a genocide
survivor who went on

00:10:51.730 --> 00:10:53.590
to become a
presidential appointee

00:10:53.590 --> 00:10:56.712
and ultimately actually had
an internship here at Google.

00:10:56.712 --> 00:10:59.170
I don't know how I met her.

00:10:59.170 --> 00:11:01.180
We met a plane
crash survivor who

00:11:01.180 --> 00:11:03.430
went on to change the airline
industry for the better.

00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:06.520
We met a tsunami survivor who
went on to become a rabbi.

00:11:06.520 --> 00:11:09.680
A domestic violence survivor who
went on to become a yoga guru.

00:11:09.680 --> 00:11:12.454
And they just kept on
getting cooler and cooler.

00:11:12.454 --> 00:11:13.870
And there was
science behind this.

00:11:13.870 --> 00:11:15.286
There had to be
science behind it.

00:11:15.286 --> 00:11:18.040
And we found it, and this
is what the book's about.

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:19.870
Each of these stories,
and all the science,

00:11:19.870 --> 00:11:24.214
kind of taught us ways to
live a life worth living.

00:11:24.214 --> 00:11:26.130
I think that's the big
takeaway from our book.

00:11:26.130 --> 00:11:28.335
We want people to
learn how to live

00:11:28.335 --> 00:11:29.460
a life that's worth living.

00:11:29.460 --> 00:11:31.480
You don't need a trauma
to experience that.

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:35.200
And that's one of our
big messages today.

00:11:35.200 --> 00:11:38.450
This was a huge collaboration,
so thank you to Mimi,

00:11:38.450 --> 00:11:40.590
thank you to Vin, thank
you to Dan Ariely today

00:11:40.590 --> 00:11:42.070
for helping us out.

00:11:42.070 --> 00:11:44.455
This is just a
spectacular moment for us.

00:11:44.455 --> 00:11:49.099
And without further ado, we will
start to read Supersurvivors.

00:11:49.099 --> 00:11:50.640
DAVID FELDMAN: So
we're going to read

00:11:50.640 --> 00:11:55.200
a sort of abridged version of
Chapter One which is titled,

00:11:55.200 --> 00:11:57.480
"To Survive or Supersurvive."

00:11:57.480 --> 00:11:58.900
LEE DANIEL KRAVETZ: Thank you.

00:11:58.900 --> 00:12:01.240
To Survive or Supersurvive.

00:12:01.240 --> 00:12:02.950
On the spectrum of
trauma survivorship,

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:05.830
everyone falls somewhere
between hiding under a rock

00:12:05.830 --> 00:12:07.790
and becoming a rock star.

00:12:07.790 --> 00:12:10.830
Asha Mevlana lay on a table
in a small examination room

00:12:10.830 --> 00:12:13.920
at St. Vincent Catholic Medical
Center in the West Village, New

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:17.700
York City, when this thought
first crossed her mind.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:21.050
She was 24 years old,
dark-haired, and beautiful.

00:12:21.050 --> 00:12:23.640
The technology industry
in 2002 was making people

00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:25.270
all over the city rich.

00:12:25.270 --> 00:12:28.680
She had a great job at a
startup, an apartment in Soho,

00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:31.790
and a pearl-shaped problem
within her left breast.

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:33.960
Asha had already guessed
that it was cancer.

00:12:33.960 --> 00:12:37.090
The lab technician's grim
look was merely confirmation.

00:12:37.090 --> 00:12:39.110
The defining moment
of her ordeal however,

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:41.570
wasn't the diagnosis.

00:12:41.570 --> 00:12:43.480
It also wasn't the
undeniable sensation

00:12:43.480 --> 00:12:45.400
that her life was
spinning out of control

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:48.210
as she underwent eight
months of chemotherapy.

00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:49.680
For Asha, the
defining moment came

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:52.170
after the doctors announced
that she was cancer-free

00:12:52.170 --> 00:12:54.380
and sent her back
into the world.

00:12:54.380 --> 00:12:56.680
While she'd been
facing her mortality,

00:12:56.680 --> 00:13:00.030
everyone else had gone on
blithely living their lives.

00:13:00.030 --> 00:13:03.480
Her co-workers talked about
the crummy New York weather,

00:13:03.480 --> 00:13:07.500
the long lines at Starbucks, and
the finalists on American Idol.

00:13:07.500 --> 00:13:11.050
Everyone seemed to place value
in such inconsequential things,

00:13:11.050 --> 00:13:12.800
that she found herself
yearning for a time

00:13:12.800 --> 00:13:14.590
when she did as well.

00:13:14.590 --> 00:13:17.840
Life as Asha once knew it simply
didn't make sense anymore.

00:13:17.840 --> 00:13:19.360
It seemed empty.

00:13:19.360 --> 00:13:21.720
So she promptly
dropped out of it.

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:24.279
I'm not a religious
person, but I prayed.

00:13:24.279 --> 00:13:25.820
Just give me a second
chance, and I'm

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:27.360
going to change my life.

00:13:27.360 --> 00:13:30.180
I'm going to do what I'm
passionate about, she says.

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:35.540
DAVID FELDMAN:
Asha is not alone.

00:13:35.540 --> 00:13:37.270
According to the
American Cancer Society,

00:13:37.270 --> 00:13:40.150
roughly 13 million
people around the world

00:13:40.150 --> 00:13:42.290
are diagnosed with
cancer each year,

00:13:42.290 --> 00:13:45.880
a number that is projected to
double in the next two decades.

00:13:45.880 --> 00:13:48.220
The journal "Neuroimaging
Clinics of North America"

00:13:48.220 --> 00:13:50.570
provides a similarly
grim outlook,

00:13:50.570 --> 00:13:53.700
with a startling 10 million
people worldwide affected

00:13:53.700 --> 00:13:56.410
every year by traumatic
brain injuries.

00:13:56.410 --> 00:13:58.150
The harsh reality
of widespread trauma

00:13:58.150 --> 00:14:00.970
becomes even more apparent
once we combine these numbers

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:03.330
with the World Health
Organization's calculation

00:14:03.330 --> 00:14:05.670
that 50 million
people a year survive

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:08.660
car wrecks, the UN's finding
that one out of every three

00:14:08.660 --> 00:14:11.480
women will be beaten,
raped, or otherwise

00:14:11.480 --> 00:14:15.160
abused during her lifetime,
and the realization

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:18.140
that these statistics
cover only a small portion

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:22.520
of the catastrophes that
befall people every day.

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:26.240
Harvard Medical School Professor
of Psychiatry, Judith Herman,

00:14:26.240 --> 00:14:29.690
calls trauma the affliction
of the powerless.

00:14:29.690 --> 00:14:32.070
The problem is
we're all powerless

00:14:32.070 --> 00:14:34.990
against the
vicissitudes of fate.

00:14:34.990 --> 00:14:37.210
She writes in her book,
"Trauma and Recovery,"

00:14:37.210 --> 00:14:41.000
quote, "traumatic events are
extraordinary not because they

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.180
occur rarely, but
because they overwhelm

00:14:44.180 --> 00:14:48.540
the ordinary human
adaptations to life," unquote.

00:14:48.540 --> 00:14:50.600
Depending on the
particular type of trauma,

00:14:50.600 --> 00:14:52.080
about a quarter
of survivors will

00:14:52.080 --> 00:14:53.860
fall into post-traumatic
stress disorder,

00:14:53.860 --> 00:14:56.950
a painful and often
debilitating condition.

00:14:56.950 --> 00:14:59.180
Others will experience
significant depression

00:14:59.180 --> 00:15:01.130
or anxiety.

00:15:01.130 --> 00:15:02.680
In the midst of
all this adversity,

00:15:02.680 --> 00:15:04.580
it's tempting to become
pessimistic and fall

00:15:04.580 --> 00:15:06.920
into a kind of
fatalistic hopelessness.

00:15:06.920 --> 00:15:09.990
It's easy to overlook
the amazing potential

00:15:09.990 --> 00:15:13.940
for resilience in us
all as human beings.

00:15:13.940 --> 00:15:15.780
Amazingly, even in
the midst of trauma,

00:15:15.780 --> 00:15:17.780
people continue
to smile, to love,

00:15:17.780 --> 00:15:21.110
to celebrate, to
create, to renew.

00:15:21.110 --> 00:15:23.320
In making this
observation, we absolutely

00:15:23.320 --> 00:15:27.020
do not mean to belittle the
impact of traumatic times,

00:15:27.020 --> 00:15:30.980
or the suffering that many have
endured and continue to endure.

00:15:30.980 --> 00:15:32.730
Suffering is real.

00:15:32.730 --> 00:15:35.920
But resilience is also real.

00:15:35.920 --> 00:15:37.870
It is an incredible
and encouraging fact

00:15:37.870 --> 00:15:40.950
about human nature, that
contrary to popular belief,

00:15:40.950 --> 00:15:42.550
after a period of
emotional turmoil,

00:15:42.550 --> 00:15:45.720
most trauma survivors
eventually recover and return

00:15:45.720 --> 00:15:47.030
to their lives.

00:15:47.030 --> 00:15:48.900
They bounce back.

00:15:48.900 --> 00:15:50.820
And in some cases they do more.

00:15:50.820 --> 00:15:52.400
They bounce forward.

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:55.010
And sometimes in
truly remarkable ways.

00:15:55.010 --> 00:15:57.690
They refocus their energies on
a new calling, on a new mission,

00:15:57.690 --> 00:16:00.610
on a new path, on helping
others who have been victimized,

00:16:00.610 --> 00:16:03.300
on education, on legal
reforms, or any number

00:16:03.300 --> 00:16:04.550
of other big goals.

00:16:04.550 --> 00:16:06.610
They move beyond
mere resilience.

00:16:06.610 --> 00:16:09.540
They transform the meaning
of their personal tragedies

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:12.020
by making them the
basis for change.

00:16:12.020 --> 00:16:13.520
We call these people
supersurvivors.

00:16:15.517 --> 00:16:17.600
LEE DANIEL KRAVETZ: In the
aftermath of her cancer

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:21.390
diagnosis, Asha paid for
improvisational violin lessons.

00:16:21.390 --> 00:16:23.250
Now before surviving
the trauma, Asha

00:16:23.250 --> 00:16:26.710
had no illusions about
making career out of music.

00:16:26.710 --> 00:16:28.720
"You mean like
playing for bar tips?

00:16:28.720 --> 00:16:30.180
No, it never crossed my mind.

00:16:30.180 --> 00:16:32.510
I was just way too
practical," she remembers.

00:16:32.510 --> 00:16:35.586
But that pragmatism didn't
survive the chemotherapy.

00:16:35.586 --> 00:16:37.210
And after working
hard for many months,

00:16:37.210 --> 00:16:40.140
she began playing electric
violin for a few amateur rock

00:16:40.140 --> 00:16:41.700
bands.

00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:43.860
Something about this
new life clicked.

00:16:43.860 --> 00:16:45.410
Perhaps it was the
unscripted nature

00:16:45.410 --> 00:16:46.980
that, much like
the music itself,

00:16:46.980 --> 00:16:49.510
was creative and freeing.

00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:51.600
A couple of months later
when a friend invited

00:16:51.600 --> 00:16:53.470
her to visit Los
Angeles for a weekend,

00:16:53.470 --> 00:16:55.030
she met a number
of local musicians

00:16:55.030 --> 00:16:57.260
who convinced her she should
get paying gigs out here

00:16:57.260 --> 00:16:59.210
in California.

00:16:59.210 --> 00:17:01.370
It would be an enormous risk.

00:17:01.370 --> 00:17:03.690
Asha's entire universe
was on the East Coast.

00:17:03.690 --> 00:17:07.319
She had no job prospects in Los
Angeles, no income, no place

00:17:07.319 --> 00:17:11.470
to live, and a million reasons
to go back to her old life.

00:17:11.470 --> 00:17:14.380
Plus although
proficient in violin,

00:17:14.380 --> 00:17:16.460
she was safely an amateur.

00:17:16.460 --> 00:17:18.660
But then again she
was also 28 years old,

00:17:18.660 --> 00:17:21.160
one of the younger survivors
of breast cancer she knew,

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:23.910
spiritually damaged, and
more than a little lost.

00:17:23.910 --> 00:17:28.460
From this perspective,
she had nothing to lose.

00:17:28.460 --> 00:17:30.700
DAVID FELDMAN: In the origin
stories of superheroes,

00:17:30.700 --> 00:17:33.560
something profound, unexpected,
and often frightening,

00:17:33.560 --> 00:17:36.780
transforms ordinary lives.

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:40.330
A massive discharge of radiation
turns a mild-mannered scientist

00:17:40.330 --> 00:17:42.390
into a hulking green avenger.

00:17:42.390 --> 00:17:46.030
The murder of another's parents
leads him to don a black mask

00:17:46.030 --> 00:17:47.560
and dedicate his
life to rescuing

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:50.081
innocent victims of
a maniacal joker.

00:17:50.081 --> 00:17:51.580
By the way, I just
want to point out

00:17:51.580 --> 00:17:54.440
that we broke no
copyrights at all in that.

00:17:54.440 --> 00:17:57.520
I bet you can't even figure
out which ones they were.

00:17:57.520 --> 00:17:59.940
But one of these scenarios
are closer to reality

00:17:59.940 --> 00:18:01.814
than we think.

00:18:01.814 --> 00:18:03.980
According to nearly two
decades of research emerging

00:18:03.980 --> 00:18:06.355
from institutions as far flung
as the University of North

00:18:06.355 --> 00:18:08.670
Carolina Charlotte and
the University of Warwick

00:18:08.670 --> 00:18:11.010
in England, the majority
of trauma survivors

00:18:11.010 --> 00:18:14.190
report some degree
of positive change.

00:18:14.190 --> 00:18:16.350
These individuals may
emerge from otherwise awful

00:18:16.350 --> 00:18:18.000
experiences primed
with something

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:21.050
like x-ray vision, which
allows them to notice value

00:18:21.050 --> 00:18:23.869
and opportunity where they might
never have seen them before.

00:18:23.869 --> 00:18:25.660
They may develop inner
strength from having

00:18:25.660 --> 00:18:29.520
lived through an experience
beyond their worst imaginings.

00:18:29.520 --> 00:18:33.340
These psychological gains are
known as post-traumatic growth.

00:18:33.340 --> 00:18:37.880
But even after experiencing
such inner growth,

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:40.240
most trauma survivors
find their outer lives

00:18:40.240 --> 00:18:41.827
returning to normal.

00:18:41.827 --> 00:18:43.285
According to
research, the majority

00:18:43.285 --> 00:18:46.440
of post-traumatic growth
is internal and private.

00:18:46.440 --> 00:18:49.870
It's what psychologists
refer to as perceived growth.

00:18:49.870 --> 00:18:52.280
Survivors report that they've
changed for the better,

00:18:52.280 --> 00:18:55.100
and they may feel the benefits
of that change, but outwardly

00:18:55.100 --> 00:18:56.820
their lives don't
look much different

00:18:56.820 --> 00:18:58.890
from before the trauma.

00:18:58.890 --> 00:19:01.860
Perceived growth
isn't fake, however.

00:19:01.860 --> 00:19:03.650
Though the research
is mixed, some studies

00:19:03.650 --> 00:19:06.540
show links between greater
perceived growth and lower

00:19:06.540 --> 00:19:09.830
emotional distress, as well
as better physical health.

00:19:09.830 --> 00:19:12.400
But sometimes people
move far beyond both

00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:14.500
the life-altering negative
effects of trauma,

00:19:14.500 --> 00:19:17.990
and the usual outcomes
of post-traumatic growth.

00:19:17.990 --> 00:19:20.990
These people don't just grow,
they revolutionize their lives.

00:19:20.990 --> 00:19:23.590
They transform and
transcend their suffering

00:19:23.590 --> 00:19:25.620
even while enduring.

00:19:25.620 --> 00:19:27.990
These supersurvivors
radically deviate

00:19:27.990 --> 00:19:30.960
from their previous life paths,
often transforming the worst

00:19:30.960 --> 00:19:34.850
thing that's happened
into the best.

00:19:34.850 --> 00:19:37.800
LEE DANIEL KRAVETZ: So Asha
has a kick-ass Viper violin.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:40.240
It's purple, and the
hourglass-shaped belly

00:19:40.240 --> 00:19:41.790
is cleaved.

00:19:41.790 --> 00:19:44.960
Instead of the classic
configuration of four strings,

00:19:44.960 --> 00:19:46.940
her fingerboard is
laced with seven.

00:19:46.940 --> 00:19:49.830
Rachmaninoff would have
been puzzled but awed.

00:19:49.830 --> 00:19:52.440
One afternoon, Asha picked up
her violin from a repair shop

00:19:52.440 --> 00:19:55.660
in downtown LA, and the guy who
had just made her instrument

00:19:55.660 --> 00:20:00.797
said he knew Dee Snider, the
lead singer of Twisted Sister,

00:20:00.797 --> 00:20:03.380
who just happened to be trying
out electric violinists to join

00:20:03.380 --> 00:20:04.442
his new tour.

00:20:04.442 --> 00:20:06.400
Although she knew her
chances were pretty slim,

00:20:06.400 --> 00:20:08.150
Asha auditioned.

00:20:08.150 --> 00:20:12.160
Two months later, she celebrated
her 30th birthday on a tour bus

00:20:12.160 --> 00:20:15.090
with one of the top metal
vocalists of all time.

00:20:15.090 --> 00:20:16.910
One opportunity led to the next.

00:20:16.910 --> 00:20:18.400
With startling
swiftness, Asha was

00:20:18.400 --> 00:20:21.090
hired to play alongside
Alanis Morissette,

00:20:21.090 --> 00:20:23.540
and after that on a US
tour with Gnarls Barkley,

00:20:23.540 --> 00:20:25.660
opening for the Red Hot
Chili Peppers in front

00:20:25.660 --> 00:20:27.800
of 30,000 people a night.

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:30.400
That same year, she
performed at the Grammys.

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:33.420
Jay Z and Mary J. Blige
both tapped her to play.

00:20:33.420 --> 00:20:35.560
Her reputation on
the rise, in 2009

00:20:35.560 --> 00:20:37.480
she played regularly
for the American Idol

00:20:37.480 --> 00:20:40.340
band and the Tonight Show.

00:20:40.340 --> 00:20:43.182
Asha had been in Los
Angeles 15 months.

00:20:43.182 --> 00:20:44.640
If someone had told
her in New York

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:47.181
that someday she'd be playing
in front of millions of people,

00:20:47.181 --> 00:20:49.050
she would have
laughed in disbelief.

00:20:49.050 --> 00:20:51.597
Yet, she'd arrived at this
place with unusual calm,

00:20:51.597 --> 00:20:53.430
as though somewhere in
the back of her mind,

00:20:53.430 --> 00:20:55.120
she always knew
she'd wind up here.

00:20:59.006 --> 00:21:00.880
DAVID FELDMAN: Asha is
one of the many people

00:21:00.880 --> 00:21:03.380
we'll meet in this book who
have dramatically altered

00:21:03.380 --> 00:21:06.750
their lives after suffering
trauma, often discovering

00:21:06.750 --> 00:21:08.520
hidden parts of
themselves or contributing

00:21:08.520 --> 00:21:11.480
to the world in ways they
never thought possible.

00:21:11.480 --> 00:21:13.830
But these people
are not superheroes.

00:21:13.830 --> 00:21:16.540
At least no more than any
other trauma survivor.

00:21:16.540 --> 00:21:18.780
In truth, they aren't
even superhuman.

00:21:18.780 --> 00:21:21.480
Their stories betray
their utter humanness.

00:21:21.480 --> 00:21:23.120
They're stumbling
and they're grasping

00:21:23.120 --> 00:21:25.328
as they wrestle with the
fundamental questions we all

00:21:25.328 --> 00:21:28.920
face, who am I, what
do I believe in,

00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:32.450
and most importantly, how
should I live my life.

00:21:32.450 --> 00:21:34.150
There is a lot
that all of us can

00:21:34.150 --> 00:21:37.260
learn from their often
haphazard but beautiful answers

00:21:37.260 --> 00:21:38.710
to these questions.

00:21:38.710 --> 00:21:42.310
To be clear, this is
not a book extolling

00:21:42.310 --> 00:21:46.180
the bright side of tragedy,
the silver lining of any cloud,

00:21:46.180 --> 00:21:49.190
or the so-called power
of positive thinking.

00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:51.360
No trauma is good.

00:21:51.360 --> 00:21:53.420
Every trauma involves suffering.

00:21:53.420 --> 00:21:56.490
There is nothing inherently
positive or indispensable

00:21:56.490 --> 00:22:00.300
about atrocities, violence,
disasters, or illness.

00:22:00.300 --> 00:22:03.540
But given that such events
are sometimes unavoidable,

00:22:03.540 --> 00:22:05.990
it is important to understand
the incredible resilience it

00:22:05.990 --> 00:22:09.000
is possible for
ordinary human beings.

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:11.720
The ability to peer into the
face of tragedy and somehow

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:14.350
emerge fundamentally
changed and able to impact

00:22:14.350 --> 00:22:17.267
the world in previously
unimagined ways.

00:22:17.267 --> 00:22:19.350
Drawing from research in
the fields of psychology,

00:22:19.350 --> 00:22:21.570
psychiatry, sociology,
anthropology,

00:22:21.570 --> 00:22:25.190
and even business, in this book
we explore why and how people

00:22:25.190 --> 00:22:28.230
transform suffering
into personal triumph.

00:22:28.230 --> 00:22:31.060
Each chapter focuses on a
particular principle identified

00:22:31.060 --> 00:22:34.540
by social scientists, including
hope, personal control,

00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:37.576
social support, forgiveness,
and spirituality.

00:22:37.576 --> 00:22:38.950
But these principles
don't always

00:22:38.950 --> 00:22:40.850
work the way you'd think.

00:22:40.850 --> 00:22:44.350
We explore how hope has little
to do with positive thinking,

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:46.260
and how despite
conventional wisdom,

00:22:46.260 --> 00:22:48.950
the disorientation and
groundlessness experienced

00:22:48.950 --> 00:22:52.770
by many people after trauma
can ultimately be advantageous.

00:22:52.770 --> 00:22:54.250
We discover why
psychologists think

00:22:54.250 --> 00:22:56.540
that's certain delusions
can be healthy,

00:22:56.540 --> 00:22:58.720
why forgiveness is good
for one's physiology

00:22:58.720 --> 00:23:01.200
as well as for the soul,
and why reflecting on death

00:23:01.200 --> 00:23:03.580
can lead to a better life.

00:23:03.580 --> 00:23:06.010
Finally, we ask what
implications these stories

00:23:06.010 --> 00:23:08.740
have for the rest of us,
regardless of whether we've

00:23:08.740 --> 00:23:10.930
survived a serious
trauma or are merely

00:23:10.930 --> 00:23:15.230
confronting the setbacks and
difficulties of everyday life.

00:23:15.230 --> 00:23:18.870
Asha's cancer was a
transformative and meaningful

00:23:18.870 --> 00:23:20.130
turning point.

00:23:20.130 --> 00:23:21.920
It afforded her the
freedom and motivation

00:23:21.920 --> 00:23:24.520
to move beyond her
previous life and build

00:23:24.520 --> 00:23:26.640
a new reality for herself.

00:23:26.640 --> 00:23:30.030
Instead of hampering
her, trauma freed her.

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:33.480
But stories like
Asha's are not typical.

00:23:33.480 --> 00:23:36.440
While trauma leaves many
people suffering, lost,

00:23:36.440 --> 00:23:38.680
and searching to
reclaim their lives,

00:23:38.680 --> 00:23:42.890
Asha's experience seems to have
provided her with direction.

00:23:42.890 --> 00:23:47.530
In this book, we discover why.

00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:48.870
